<TITLE> City 'on alert' </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Nov 18 (bdnews24.com)  Dhaka was on 'high alert' Wednesday, as security was raised up another notch at the country's highest court, Dhaka Central Jail, their surrounding buildings and streets and other key areas of the city ahead of the Bangabandhu appeals verdict. The five-member bench of the Appellate Division, headed by Justice Mohammed Tafazzal Islam, is expected hand down the verdict in the courtroom of the chief justice at 11am Thursday. The apex court set the final judgement day on Nov 12 after the 29 days of appeals proceedings. All security has been beefed up around the court premises ahead of the verdict of the politically sensitive case. Security for the justices was tightened earlier, after the attorney general received a death threat. Additional deputy commissioner of police Mohammed Walid Hossain told bdnews24.com Thursday some 592 police members will be deployed at 33 points under the Ramna zone, site of the High Court, and several checkpoints will also be set up where police will be present with metal detectors. In the afternoon, ten close circuit cameras and monitoring rooms were installed around the High Court premises. A walk-through metal detector was installed at the entrance of the designated courtroom as part of heightened security measures. Police cameramen will record footage of the court premises on Thursday, while police and Rapid Action Battalion with the assistance of the dog squads are already posted at the three entrances. Prohibitions are imposed on non-stickered cars. Trespassing by public is also banned, olice said. Meanwhile, security inside and outside the central jail is also beefed up. Armed police are installed atop high buildings in the vicinity with binoculars. Additional police have been deployed at the jail perimeter, deputy inspector general of prisons Golam Haider told bdnews24.com. Plain clothes police are also active, he said. The five, appealing their death sentences in the case, are Syed Faruq Rahman, Sultan Shahriar Rashid Khan, Bazlul Huda, Mohiuddin Ahmed and AKM Mohiuddin Ahmed. A special team, headed by a deputy jailer, has been formed to ensure security for the convicts. Five guards, one for each convict, have been assigned round-the-clock on three-hour shifts. These guards are thoroughly frisked before they are allowed to be on duty. A special intelligence team has been formed on top of that to secretly monitor all security arrangements. Security measures around the Bangabandhu Museum at Road No 32, the family home in 1975 and the site of the assassination, have also been tightened. UK and US diplomats and embassy staff told bdnews24.com they were advised by their missions to not venture from the diplomatic zone and to avoid crowds. 'No disruption to daily life' Home minister Sahara Khatun said there would be no bar to movement on Thursday, though law enforcers are ready to tackle any security situation. "No need to panic," said the home minister. "There is no bar in the movement of the public. Law enforcers will search only those they deem suspicious," she said. On whether the government fears any acts of sabotage the minister said: "Nothing will happen, we pray." The ruling Awami League has asked its supporters not to go overboard and stage rallies and processions following the verdict. bdnews
